# Step 2: Analyze the Proposal


Numbers of volunteers over the years have been decreasing due to the various reasons humans have- whether it be a busy lifestyle, laziness, or difficulty finding volunteer opportunities in the area. However, Serve Central is your next favorite web and mobile application making volunteer numbers rise through easier access of volunteer opportunities and sign up all in one simple place!

# Step 3: Enhancing an Architecture

## Step 3.1 Architecture Change Proposal



In my opinion, the best architecture type would be Git for ServeCentral. This is because with 
the Git architecture type, you can either pull information from the Git repo of ServeCentral and
use that for your own benefit (if you are an organization), or you can input your own volunteer
information into the official ServeCentral repo (this would be done if you are a volunteer agency 
and you're trying to put out your information so that others can know about your volunteer
opportunity). 

The second requirement that this architecture pattern fulfills is that it would
allow organizations to grab what the ServeCentral has on their repo, and change it, and have it
be customized to whatever they want. They can then input this version into their own website, mobile
app, or whatever else they choose.  

The only drawback is that if organizations are grabbing this information from Serve Central's 
Git, they could change it almost "too much" and make it not align with the mission and vision of 
what Serve Central had in mind... this is an issue if someone sees that this goes back to Serve Central,
it could give them a bad look. This is the only main drawback that I can think of. 



## Step 3.2 Revised Architecture Diagram

The following image serves to show how both requirements can be fulfilled within the Git architectural pattern.
The reason both of these requirements are fulfilled is because the first requirement of needing to be able
to input and receive data is established through the first set of arrows that forks the Git repo- which then allows
the organization that forked it to either grab info or change info. The second requirement is fulfilled because
these organizations can fork from the repo, but take it further and create their own interfaces and change it and 
publish it as their own with their additions that best fit them.

# Step 4: Scaling an Architecture


It is very obvious that we need an architecture pattern that allows for quick upgrades to its information,
enough storage within itself, allows queries similar in type to a lot of SQL queries, and allow outsiders
to view information without interacting with it and changing it. In my opinion, the simplest and best
solution to this set of needs is the MVC model. I think this is the best option because it allows for
a model to be updated and viewed, a controller to allow things like queries to happen within the structure, 
and a view to allow those that want to examine volunteer numbers for business/grant purposes. This is practically
the best structure because each of these things can be done all together, or if you only wish to view information, 
you also have the option of just viewing.
